<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1789,1922]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,1789,1814]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Natural enemies.</emphasis>
Two caterpillars collected at Kibwezi (
<collectionCode box="[854,937,1790,1814]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">MJWC</collectionCode>
89/29) were parasitized by a solitary larval endoparasitoid 
<taxonomicName box="[323,508,1825,1850]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Microgasterinae">Microgasterinae</taxonomicName>
, the larvae of which emerged from fifth instar host caterpillars to spin a 
<quantity box="[1321,1380,1825,1850]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
long white cocoon in a very loose flocculence of white silk in the leaf shelter (Figure 5.1). The adult emerged after 11 days.
</paragraph>
